x=23
print(x)
23
Here, x=variable and 23 is value. Here, x automatically knew that 23 is number.You can check that by using ( type(x)) ANSWER:int
Here, y='Mint Choclate Chips' print(y) ANSWER:Mint Choclate Chips >  type(y)> ANSWER:str
You can add several row by (+)

y='Strawberry chocolate'
print(y) 
ANSWER>Strawberry chocolate 
If you assign y to Mint Choclate Chips then
y='Strawberry chocolate' 
y='Mint Choclate Chips' 
print(y) 
ANSWER : Mint Choclate Chips

X,Y,Z='Choclate','Vanilla','Sour Candy'
print(X)
print(Y)
print(Z)

ANSWER:
Choclate
Vanilla
Sour Candy

X=Y=Z='Root Beer Float'
print(X)
print(Y)
print(Z)

ANSWER:
Root Beer Float
Root Beer Float
Root Beer Float

ice_cream=['Choclate','Vanilla','Sour Candy']
X,Y,Z=ice_cream
print(X)
print(Y)
print(Z)
ANSWER:
Choclate
Vanilla
Sour Candy


THERE ARE MANY DIFFERENT WAYS TO WRITE VARIABLE:

#Camel Case
#Test Variable Case
testVariableCase='Vanilla Swirl'

#Pascal Case
#Test Variable Case
TestVariableCase='Vanilla Swirl'
(Note: T is capital)

#Snake Case
#Test Variable Case
test_variable_case='Vanilla Swirl'

(Use Snake case, it improve readability)


you can do this 
